// Figure 4.4: Event-Driven Checkout Flow (Saga Pattern)
// Basket → RabbitMQ → Ordering (async decoupling)

// ==================== ACTORS ====================
Frontend [icon: react, color: blue]
Ocelot Gateway [icon: aws-api-gateway, color: orange]
Basket API [icon: shopping-cart, color: green]
Redis [icon: redis, color: green]
RabbitMQ [icon: rabbitmq, color: yellow]
Ordering Consumer [icon: message-circle, color: purple]
Ordering API [icon: clipboard-list, color: purple]
SQL Server [icon: mssql, color: red]

// ==================== SYNCHRONOUS PHASE ====================
Frontend > Ocelot Gateway : POST /Basket/Checkout
Ocelot Gateway > Basket API : Route to service
Basket API > Redis : Get cart data
Basket API > RabbitMQ : Publish BasketCheckoutEvent
Basket API > Redis : Delete cart
Basket API > Ocelot Gateway : 202 Accepted
Ocelot Gateway > Frontend : Checkout initiated

// ==================== ASYNCHRONOUS PHASE ====================
RabbitMQ > Ordering Consumer : Deliver event
Ordering Consumer > Ordering API : CheckoutOrderCommand
Ordering API > SQL Server : INSERT Order
Ordering API > Ordering Consumer : Order created

// ==================== SAGA CHARACTERISTICS ====================
// - No distributed transaction (2PC avoided)
// - Eventual consistency via async events
// - User gets 202 Accepted immediately
// - Order creation happens reliably via messaging
